---
import Slide from "../components/Slide.astro";
---

<Slide>
	<h2>From landmarks to meaning</h2>
	<div class="pipeline">
		<div class="step">
			<span class="big">21 × (x, y, z)</span>
			<span class="caption">one hand =<br />63 numbers</span>
		</div>
		<span class="arrow fragment" data-fragment-index="1">→</span>
		<div class="step fragment" data-fragment-index="1">
			<span class="big">normalize</span>
			<span class="caption">wrist at origin,<br />scale &amp; mirror out</span>
		</div>
		<span class="arrow fragment" data-fragment-index="2">→</span>
		<div class="step fragment" data-fragment-index="2">
			<span class="big">classify</span>
			<span class="caption">tiny model (kNN)<br />over 63-dim vectors</span>
		</div>
		<span class="arrow fragment" data-fragment-index="3">→</span>
		<div class="step highlight fragment" data-fragment-index="3">
			<span class="big">“A”</span>
			<span class="caption">a hand shape<br />becomes a label</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">No giant model needed — the landmarker already did the hard part</li>
		<li class="fragment">This is exactly how a <strong>sign alphabet</strong> becomes machine-readable</li>
	</ul>
	<aside class="notes">
		Once you have clean, normalized landmarks, gesture classification is almost embarrassingly simple — a kNN over a
		few dozen recorded samples per letter works live on stage. The heavy lifting is all in the landmark model.
	</aside>
</Slide>

<style>
	.pipeline {
		display: flex;
		align-items: stretch;
		justify-content: center;
		gap: 0.4em;
		margin: 1em 0;
	}
	.step {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		justify-content: center;
		gap: 0.3em;
		padding: 0.5em 0.6em;
		border: 1px solid #334155;
		border-radius: 10px;
		background: rgb(15 23 42 / 0.6);

		&.highlight {
			border-color: #4ade80;
		}
	}
	.big {
		font-size: 0.75em;
		font-weight: bold;
	}
	.caption {
		font-size: 0.4em;
		color: #94a3b8;
	}
	.arrow {
		align-self: center;
		color: #4ade80;
	}
	ul {
		font-size: 0.7em;
	}
</style>
